{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f47fde1c-cfab-4f50-805e-06cd0c126498","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n## Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\nUse **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform) or **WinDbg/lldb** depending on your OS:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Start interactive analysis\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nOnce inside the analyzer, run these commands in order:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` | Print the last exception (usually the crash cause) |\n| `clrstack` | Show managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects for context |\n| `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` | Inspect other threads |\n\n**Typical workflow:**\n1. `pe` — shows the exception type/message (e.g., `NullReferenceException`, `StackOverflowException`)\n2. `clrstack` — shows exactly where it happened\n3. If the crashing thread isn't the current one, use `clrthreads` → `setthread` → `clrstack` to find it\n\nWould you like help running any of these commands, or do you have specific error details from the dump you'd like to troubleshoot?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab03c841-1fe5-4152-bf6c-9dd34618ad2e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the skill is not appropriate here. Let me help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":453,"requestId":"2059:2211CA:76BFBC:8A2CB9:69F01359"},"id":"1d8a0afb-93ff-43b6-9149-8cf4d1505561","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:5